  "Title": "Latent Hierarchical Self-Refinement (LHSR): Eliciting Endogenous Syntactic Structure in Non-Autoregressive Translation through Progressive Self-Supervision",
  "Experiment": "We will implement LHSR using mBART-50 as the base architecture, evaluating on WMT’14 En-De, WMT’16 En-Ro, and FLORES’200 low-resource pairs (e.g., Swahili-English). The implementation proceeds in three phases: (1) Preprocessing: Extract cross-lingual subword similarity matrices using mBERT/mT5 embeddings; compute initial pseudo-alignments via cosine similarity. No external parses or alignments are used beyond this initialization. (2) Model Design: Modify mBART’s decoder with three gated blocks corresponding to stages: the first processes raw token inputs with alignment loss; the second applies a differentiable K-means-like clustering over self-attention maps to detect phrase boundaries; the third performs self-distillation using an EMA-updated teacher model. Introduce a progressive masking scheduler that evolves from token-level to constituent-level masking based on dynamic attention entropy thresholds. (3) Training Curriculum: Begin with standard NAT objectives (masked language modeling + alignment contrast); in Phase 2, add structural infilling loss over clustered spans; in Phase 3, activate self-distillation with KL divergence between student and teacher structural representations. Baselines include vanilla NAT, CMLM, and syntax-augmented NATs (e.g., those using UDPipe trees). Evaluation includes BLEU, CHRF++, COMET, syntactic accuracy (via Stanza parser agreement), and human evaluation on fluency and grammaticality. We conduct extensive ablations on each component and perform diagnostic probing to track syntactic knowledge emergence across layers and stages.",
